sec.p:
ϕΣμTRMC as determined by the TRMC technique is representative of the local sum of electron and hole mobilities, in the plane of the substrate, averaged over the whole sample. In an attempt to draw an analogy between the spectroscopic analysis and HJPT operation from the viewpoint of in-plane charge transport, we carried out transient photoconductivity (TPC) measurement to determine long-range lateral mobility ϕΣμTPC38,39. Our TPC study (Fig. 3d) was carried out using a pulsed laser with a range of excitation densities to illuminate the pristine FACs and FACs/OSC bilayer stacks made on the glass substrates with two pre-deposited in-plane Au electrodes. The schematic drawing of the experimental setup is shown in Supplementary Fig. 13. Knowing the photoconductivity as a function of the laser excitation density (Supplementary Fig. 14), we estimated the long-range sum of electron and hole mobility within the FACs films using a simple relationship reported previously, i.e., σTPC=eIabsϕΣμTPC\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\sigma _{\mathrm{TPC}} = eI_{\mathrm{abs}}\phi {\mathrm{\Sigma }}\mu _{{\mathrm{TPC}}}$$\end{document} where e is elementary charge, Iabs is absorbed excitation density as determined from the laser pulse intensity and the absorbance of the film38. As such, we were able to determine the long-range lateral mobility ΣμTPC to be 0.69, 0.52, 0.19 and 0.22 cm2 V−1 s−1 (at the lowest excitation density of 1.57 × 1017 cm−3) for the pristine FACs, FACs/C8-BTBT, FACs/C16-IDTBT and FACs/blend 1:1, respectively. Notably, these long-range mobilities of the pristine FACs and FACs/OSC bilayers are in good agreement with the average local mobilities determined by TRMC.

Photoresponsivity (R) is an important figure of merit for photodetectors and is defined as the ratio of photo-generated current (Iph) to the incident optical power (Popt). It can be calculated by the equation:1R=IphPopt=Iillum−IdarkEopt⋅a\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$R = \frac{{I_{{\mathrm{ph}}}}}{{P_{{\mathrm{opt}}}}} = \frac{{I_{{\mathrm{illum}}} - I_{{\mathrm{dark}}}}}{{E_{{\mathrm{opt}}} \cdot a}}$$\end{document}where, Iillum is the current under illumination, Idark is the current in dark, Eopt is the  optical power density measured by the power sensors and a is the device area. The device area for transistors is the area enclosed by the channel length and channel width, while that for diodes is defined by the overlap between two electrodes.

Photogain (G) defines the efficiency of optical power converted into measurable electrical current and can be calculated by the equation:2G=IphPopt⋅hvq\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$G = \frac{{I_{{\mathrm{ph}}}}}{{P_{{\mathrm{opt}}}}} \cdot \frac{{hv}}{q}$$\end{document}where hv is the photon energy. In photodiode an absorbed photon can generate at best one electron-hole pair, corresponding to the maximum obtainable gain of 1. In contrast, the ohmic contact in photoconductor and phototransistor favours charge carriers circulation for several cycles before recombination, hence every single absorbed photon can result in more than one electron detected, i.e., photogain larger than unity is possible. The gain mechanism in such structures can be explained by a trap-assisted model and the corresponding photoconductive gain (Gpc) can be expressed by73Gpc=τt\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
